**Template literals** are a JavaScript feature (introduced in **ES6 / ES2015**) that make working with strings **easier, cleaner, and more powerful**.

They use **backticks (` `)** instead of quotes.

***

## ‚úÖ Basic Syntax

```js
const name = "Raja";
const message = `Hello, ${name}!`;
console.log(message);
```

üëâ Output:

    Hello, Raja!

***

## ‚úÖ Key Features of Template Literals

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ String Interpolation (`${}`)

You can embed:

*   Variables
*   Expressions
*   Function calls

```js
const a = 10;
const b = 20;

console.log(`Sum is ${a + b}`);
```

‚úÖ Much cleaner than:

```js
console.log("Sum is " + (a + b));
```

***

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Multi-line Strings (No `\n` Needed)

```js
const text = `This is line one
This is line two
This is line three`;
```

‚úÖ Old way:

```js
const text = "This is line one\nThis is line two\nThis is line three";
```

***

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Expression Evaluation

You‚Äôre not limited to variables:

```js
const price = 100;
const tax = 18;

console.log(`Total price: ‚Çπ${price + price * tax / 100}`);
```

***

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Function Calls Inside Template Literals

```js
function getGreeting(name) {
  return `Hello ${name}`;
}

console.log(`${getGreeting("Reddy")}, welcome back!`);
```

***

### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Conditional Logic

```js
const isLoggedIn = true;

const message = `User is ${isLoggedIn ? "logged in" : "logged out"}`;
```

***

